data.content:
Here's the full performance analysis for this hot-path logging library.

---

## Scan Execution Checklist

| Recipe | Hits |
|--------|------|
| `.IndexOf(string)` without StringComparison | 0 |
| `.Substring(` | 0 |
| `.StartsWith`/`.EndsWith` without StringComparison | 0 |
| `.Contains(string)` without StringComparison | 0 |
| Sync-over-async | 0 |
| `new HttpClient` / `new Regex(` / `new JsonSerializerOptions` | 0 |
| `.ToLower()`/`.ToUpper()` | 0 |
| `.ToLowerInvariant()` | 1 |
| Chained `.Replace()` (3+) | 0 |
| `params` keyword | 2 |
| LINQ (`.Select`/`.Where`/`.Take`/`.Aggregate`/`.Any`) | 17 |
| `.ToList()` | 1 |
| `.ToArray()` | 3 |
| `new List<` (per-call) | 1 |
| `static readonly Dictionary<` | 0 |
| Unsealed classes | 1 of 1 |
| Sealed classes | 0 |

## Positive Findings

- ✅ No sync-over-async blocking
- ✅ No `Substring` allocations
- ✅ No string comparison without `StringComparison`
- ✅ No regex, HttpClient, or serialization issues
- ✅ `List<string?>` pre-sized with capacity 8 (L91)

---

## Findings

#### 1. LINQ Chains on Hot Path (17 instances)
🔴 **Critical**

**Impact:** Every `Humanize()` call allocates 6–10 objects (enumerators, delegates, intermediate collections) just from LINQ. At millions of calls/min this creates severe GC pressure.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L128, L140, L143, L146, L149, L158, L169, L244, L261-262, L270-272, L284, L304`

**Fix:** Replace LINQ chains with `foreach` loops writing into pre-sized lists or spans.

`SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan` (L133–150) — 3 chained LINQ operators + list materialization:
```csharp
// Before: 3 enumerator allocs + delegate allocs + list alloc
private static List<string?> SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    IEnumerable<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    if (!countEmptyUnits)
        timeParts = timeParts.Where(x => x != null);
    timeParts = timeParts.Take(precision);
    if (countEmptyUnits)
        timeParts = timeParts.Where(x => x != null);
    return [.. timeParts];
}

// After: single pass, zero enumerator/delegate allocation
private static List<string?> SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    List<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    var result = new List<string?>(precision);
    int taken = 0;
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
    {
        if (taken >= precision)
            break;
        if (countEmptyUnits)
        {
            taken++;
            if (part != null)
                result.Add(part);
        }
        else
        {
            if (part != null)
            {
                result.Add(part);
                taken++;
            }
        }
    }
    return result;
}
```

`IsContainingOnlyNullValue` (L127–128) — accepts `IEnumerable`, allocates an enumerator:
```csharp
// Before
private static bool IsContainingOnlyNullValue(IEnumerable<string?> timeParts) =>
    !timeParts.Any(x => x != null);

// After — accepts the concrete List, no enumerator/delegate allocation
private static bool IsContainingOnlyNullValue(List<string?> timeParts)
{
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
        if (part != null) return false;
    return true;
}
```

`ConcatenateTimeSpanParts` (L155–171) — `.Where().ToList()` + `.Take()`:
```csharp
// Before
var parts = timeSpanParts.Where(x => x != null).ToList();
var allButLast = string.Join(collectionSeparator, parts.Take(parts.Count - 1));

// After — filter into pre-sized list, use range indexer
var parts = new List<string>(timeParts.Count);
foreach (var p in timeParts)
    if (p != null) parts.Add(p!);
// Use List<T>.GetRange or StringBuilder for joining
```

`HumanizeDisplayStrings` (L266–286) — `.Select().Where().ToArray()` chain:
```csharp
// Before
var itemsArray = strings
    .Select(item => item == null ? string.Empty : item.Trim())
    .Where(item => !string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(item))
    .ToArray();

// After — single pass, no intermediate allocations
var items = new List<string>();
foreach (var item in strings)
{
    var trimmed = item?.Trim();
    if (!string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(trimmed))
        items.Add(trimmed!);
}
```

---

#### 2. `enum.ToString().ToLowerInvariant()` Per Call (1 instance)
🔴 **Critical**

**Impact:** 2 string allocations per time unit per call — `ToString()` boxes and allocates, then `ToLowerInvariant()` allocates another string. Only 8 possible enum values — perfect for caching.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L175`

**Fix:** Cache lowercase unit names in a static array indexed by enum value.

```csharp
// Before
var unitName = unit.ToString().ToLowerInvariant();

// After
private static readonly string[] s_unitNames =
    ["year", "month", "week", "day", "hour", "minute", "second", "millisecond"];

private static string FormatTimePart(int value, TimeUnit unit, CultureInfo culture)
{
    var unitName = s_unitNames[(int)unit];
    return value == 1 ? $"{value} {unitName}" : $"{value} {unitName}s";
}
```

---

#### 3. `params` Array Allocation Per Call (2 instances)
🟡 **Moderate**

**Impact:** Every call to `Transform()` allocates a `T[]`, even for the common 1-argument case. On a hot path this is one avoidable allocation per call.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L303`

**Fix:** Add a 1-argument overload to avoid the array allocation for the common case.

```csharp
public static string Transform(
    this string input, CultureInfo culture, IStringTransformer transformer) =>
    transformer.Transform(input);
```

---

#### 4. Double `.Select()` in Object Formatter (1 instance)
🟡 **Moderate**

**Impact:** Two chained `.Select()` calls create 2 enumerator + 2 delegate allocations per call. Can be fused into one.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L259-262`

**Fix:** Fuse into a single `.Select(o => objectFormatter(o)?.ToString())`.

---

#### 5. `DefaultCollectionFormatter` Not Sealed (1 of 1 class)
🟡 **Moderate**

**Impact:** JIT cannot devirtualize the `virtual` method calls. Sealing enables inlining.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L208`

**Fix:** Add `sealed` keyword — `public sealed class DefaultCollectionFormatter`. **Caveat:** Only if no subclasses exist.

---

#### 6. `CreateTimePartsWithNoTimeValue` Allocates a List for Zero-Time Case (1 instance)
ℹ️ **Info**

**Impact:** `[noTimeValue]` creates a `List<string?>` only to index `[0]`. Minor since it's the zero-timespan edge case.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L76, L124-125`

**Fix:** Return the string directly instead of wrapping in a list: `return "no time";`

---

## Summary

| Severity | Count | Top Issue |
|----------|-------|-----------|
| 🔴 Critical | 2 | LINQ chains allocating 6-10 objects per `Humanize()` call |
| 🟡 Moderate | 3 | `params` array, double `.Select()`, unsealed class |
| ℹ️ Info | 1 | List allocation for edge case |

The biggest win is **finding #1**: replacing LINQ with `foreach` loops eliminates the majority of per-call allocations. Combined with **finding #2** (caching enum names), you'd remove ~8–12 allocations per `Humanize()` call — critical at millions of invocations/minute.

> ⚠️ **Disclaimer:** These results are generated by an AI assistant and are non-deterministic. Findings may include false positives, miss real issues, or suggest changes that are incorrect for your specific context. Always verify recommendations with benchmarks and human review before applying changes to production code.
